"Abstract There have been two more significant Federal Court rulings in recent months. It is becoming apparent that for a variety of reasons, a majority of important technology-related litigation is occurring in the Federal Court rather than the State Supreme Courts. On 14 September, 1990, the Full Court of the Federal Court handed down a landmark ruling on software copyright in Autodesk Inc v Dyason and on 1 October, 1990, a trial judge in Melbourne issued an interesting judgment on misleading conduct by a supplier in Hughes v Canon Australia Pty Ltd. The Autodesk case has already attracted a considerable amount of attention because it deals with an uncertain area of the law. (See (1990–1991) 6 CLSR 33) It was the first time the Full Court had ruled on the 1984 amendments to the Copyright Act 1968 (Cth). The Canon case is also important, even though it did not write new law - it exemplifies the approach of the Federal Court towards loose promises made by equipment suppliers. Having dealt with Autodesk in the last issue this case note concentrates on Hughes . Gordon Hughes Reports."
